workflow EnrichSprintsArchitect
  goal: "Opus reads sprint_plan + spec_analysis, drafts a project-wide contract, then iterates sprint-by-sprint calling write_enriched_sprint once per sprint (Sonnet writes each)."
  start: Start
  exit: Exit

  defaults
    max_retries: 1
    fidelity: summary:medium

  tool Start
    label: Start
    timeout: 5s
    command:
      printf 'begin'

  tool Exit
    label: Exit
    timeout: 5s
    command:
      printf 'done'

  agent architect
    label: "Architect (Opus)"
    model: claude-opus-4-6
    provider: anthropic
    reasoning_effort: high
    max_turns: 50
    fallback_target: Exit
    prompt:
      You are the architect for sprint enrichment. Same shape as the existing `write_sprint_docs` agent — one tool call per sprint — but the writing tool delegates each sprint to a mid-tier model (Sonnet).

      Inputs:
      - `.ai/sprint_plan.md` — merged sprint plan (decomposition output)
      - `.ai/spec_analysis.md` — upstream spec analysis with FR-numbered requirements

      ## Step 1: Read both input files

      Read `.ai/sprint_plan.md` and `.ai/spec_analysis.md` in full.

      ## Step 2: Author the project-wide contract → write to `.ai/contract.md`

      The contract is the cross-sprint architectural surface — pinned once, passed to every per-sprint generation call. Required sections:

      ### Stack & runtime
      - Language(s) and version
      - Package manager and key third-party libraries (web framework, ORM, test framework, validation, auth) — each with exact import name
      - Anything explicitly excluded

      ### Project-wide conventions
      - Error handling idiom (exception shape, error-wrap pattern)
      - Naming conventions (file/module casing, test file naming)
      - Test framework + test organization rules
      - Async vs sync, logging conventions

      ### Sprint file-ownership map
      For every sprint in the plan, list the files it owns. Note shared files with explicit ownership rules (e.g. "Sprint 001 OWNS models.py; Sprint 002+ APPENDS to it").

      ### Cross-sprint type/symbol ownership map (load-bearing)
      For every type, function, or constant that crosses sprint boundaries, declare the owning sprint AND the **exact name and shape** — exact field names with types, exact function signatures including method-vs-free-function and error/exception returns. This pins what later sprints will import. Underspecification here is the failure mode.

      ### Cross-sprint dependency edges
      Directed graph of which sprints depend on which.

      ### Mandatory rules across all sprints
      Project-wide rules: import conventions, no-circular-imports rules, schema conventions, test isolation.

      Save the contract to `.ai/contract.md` using the write tool.

      ## Step 3: For each sprint in the plan, call `write_enriched_sprint`

      The tool reads `.ai/contract.md` automatically — do NOT pass `contract` in the args. Per-call args are minimal:
      - `path`: `SPRINT-NNN.md` (zero-padded 3-digit ID)
      - `description`: a per-sprint slice including:
        - title, scope summary, FRs covered
        - **File breakdown — categorize EVERY file:**
          - `New files:` — files this sprint creates that don't exist yet
          - `Modified files:` — files that already exist from prior sprints and this sprint extends (appends models, adds dispatch entries). Use the contract's file-ownership map (e.g. "Sprint 001 OWNS models.py; Sprint 002+ APPENDS") to categorize. Misclassifying a modified file as new causes the local executor to overwrite prior sprint contributions.
        - types/functions this sprint defines (NAMES — fields pinned in contract)
        - cross-sprint dependencies it consumes
        - exact validation commands
        - **Infrastructure & setup specifics (load-bearing for sprint 001 and any later sprint that introduces new build/config infrastructure):** include verbatim content for every config file the sprint creates — package manifests (`pyproject.toml`, `package.json`, `Cargo.toml`, `go.mod`), build-system config (`[tool.hatch.build.targets.wheel]`, `tsconfig.json`, `vite.config.ts`, `webpack.config.js`), test-runner config (`pytest.ini` sections, `vitest.config.ts`), linter configs, Dockerfiles, CI files, env templates. Do not hand-wave these — provide the exact text the generator should transcribe. The downstream local generator cannot invent build-system internals (package-discovery rules, wheel paths, dep resolver groups, path mappings); if it has to guess, it'll be wrong in subtle ways. Take the time to nail these down once at sprint 001, and again whenever a later sprint introduces new infrastructure (e.g., a frontend `package.json`, an alembic migration setup, a Docker compose file).
      - `output_dir`: `.ai/sprints`

      Iterate over every sprint in the plan. Make exactly one `write_enriched_sprint` call per sprint listed. The natural endpoint is when every sprint in `.ai/sprint_plan.md` has a corresponding tool call. After the last sprint, output a single confirmation line and stop.

      ## Tools available
      - read (for inputs)
      - write (for `.ai/contract.md` only)
      - write_enriched_sprint (one call per sprint)

      Do NOT write SPRINT-NNN.md files yourself — only the tool produces those.

  edges
    Start -> architect
    architect -> Exit
